      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/icon-bird-4.png" alt="Sharp-tailed Sandpiper">
        
        <p>Sharp-tailed Sandpiper</p>
         
        <p>Sharpies love Australia’s inland wetlands and visit them whenever rains drench the desert sands, and in dry years they bring a touch of the red centre to grey coastal shorebird flocks.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/sharp-tailed-sandpiper">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/Ruddy-Turnstone-silhouette.png" alt="Ruddy Turnstone">
        
        <p>Ruddy Turnstone</p>
         
        <p>Australia is a ruddy long way from their arctic breeding grounds, but these frequent flyers return to their favourite Aussie beaches each year.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/ruddy-turnstone">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/icon-bird-1.png" alt="Bar-tailed Godwit">
        
        <p>Bar-tailed Godwit</p>
         
        <p>Bar-tailed Godwits fly such a long distance in a lifetime — the equivalent of flying to the moon — so they may have a Plan B if things don’t work out on this planet, but it would be our loss.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/bar-tailed-godwit">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/Great-Knot-silhouette.png" alt="Great Knot">
        
        <p>Great Knot</p>
         
        <p>2016 is crunch time for Great Knots. With a population decline averaging 4 per cent each year, we must save the mudflats that support the shellfish they rely on.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/great-knot">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/Grey-Plover-silhouette.png" alt="Grey Plover">
        
        <p>Grey Plover</p>
         
        <p>Watch out plover lovers — this migration season, Grey Plovers flying between Australia and the Arctic will reveal their the main stop-over sites, courtesy of satellite-tracking technology.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/grey-plover">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      <div class="prof-cont-box">
        <img src="images/icon-bird-6.png" alt="Eastern Curlew">
        
        <p>Eastern Curlew</p>
         
        <p>Eastern Curlews are really far out when it comes to birds. They are the largest of all shorebirds and call their own name ‘Cuuuurrlew’.</p>
        
        <a href="http://birdlife.org.au/bird-profile/eastern-curlew">Read more</a></a>
        
      </div>
      
      
  


